column2: Recursively assigning properties on objects may cause accidental modification of a built-in prototype object.
column4: Properties are copied from [["source"|"relative:///lib/options/compatibility.js:143:19:143:24"]] to [["target"|"relative:///lib/options/compatibility.js:149:7:149:12"]] without guarding against prototype pollution.

column2: Prepending a backslash to an ordinary character in a string does not have any effect, and may make regular expressions constructed from this string behave unexpectedly.
column4: The escape sequence '\W' is equivalent to just 'W', so the sequence is not a character class when it is used in a [["regular expression"|"relative:///lib/optimizer/level-1/optimize.js:591:55:591:103"]].

column2: Regular expressions without anchors can be vulnerable to bypassing.
column4:
Misleading operator precedence. The subexpression '^hsl\(\s*[\-\.\d]+\s*,\s*[\.\d]+%\s*,\s*[\.\d]+%\s*\)' is anchored at the beginning, but the other parts of this regular expression are not
Misleading operator precedence. The subexpression 'hsla\(\s*[\-\.\d]+\s*,\s*[\.\d]+%\s*,\s*[\.\d]+%\s*,\s*[\.\d]+\s*\)$' is anchored at the end, but the other parts of this regular expression are not

column2: Regular expressions without anchors can be vulnerable to bypassing.
column4:
Misleading operator precedence. The subexpression '^rgb\(\s*[\d]{1,3}\s*,\s*[\d]{1,3}\s*,\s*[\d]{1,3}\s*\)' is anchored at the beginning, but the other parts of this regular expression are not
Misleading operator precedence. The subexpression 'rgba\(\s*[\d]{1,3}\s*,\s*[\d]{1,3}\s*,\s*[\d]{1,3}\s*,\s*[\.\d]+\s*\)$' is anchored at the end, but the other parts of this regular expression are not
